In JIRA 7.0 / 7.1.4 OSWorkflowManager.doWorkflowActionInsideTxn()  does:
            try {
                wf.doAction(wfid, from.getAction(), inputs);

                // save the issue updates - the generate change history function stores the issue as well, but if it has been modified by some post functions
                // after that we need to store the issue again.
                issue.store();

                // commit the TX
                txn.commit();
            } finally {
where wf.doAction() executes all post-functions, configured on the workflow's transition. They may affect the current issue and update (store()) it. There are explicit post-functions on the transition that explicitly store the issue (twice) and they cannot be removed. 

The problem is that when implementing a logic a subtask to call a transition on its parent issue, while the parent is doing actually a transition (for example: on a specific parent's transition a subtask is created, that completes automatically and triggers the next parent transition) this explicit issue.store() in the first parent transition  (deep in the stack) overrides the changes and state that were done on  the parent issue during the nested parent transition (top of the call stack). 

To sum up:
- issue.store() is redundant here as it is the third time the issue is stored while doing a workflow transition (action)
- issue.store() is harmful here as it overwrites the changes happened on the issue during the wf.doAction() call

